Chapter 1

Hello everyone, in this course we will learn how to write programs in the \texttt{C}C\texttt{C}C  programming language.

Before starting to learn how to write code in \texttt{C}C\texttt{C}C, you need to understand what a programming language is used for.

A programming language could be defined as an intermediary language between the user (you) and the computer.

Now the question we might ask is, how does a computer manage to understand a language?

The thing is, the computer doesn't understand... In fact a computer can only understand one language and that language is binary code. Now we want to know what binary language is. Binary language is simply a language where words are made up of 0000  and 1111.  To be more formal, we know that to construct sentences in English we need to know English words, and to construct words in English we need to know the English alphabet. Thus, if AAAA represents the English alphabet, then AAAA will represent all the letters we know i.e.i.e.i.e.i.e. A = \{a,b,c,d,e,f,g,h,i,j,k,l,m,n,o,p,q,r,s,t,u,v,w,x,y,z\}A={a,b,c,d,e,f,g,h,i,j,k,l,m,n,o,p,q,r,s,t,u,v,w,x,y,z}A = \{a,b,c,d,e,f,g,h,i,j,k,l,m,n,o,p,q,r,s,t,u,v,w,x,y,z\}A={a,b,c,d,e,f,g,h,i,j,k,l,m,n,o,p,q,r,s,t,u,v,w,x,y,z}. Well, for the binary alphabet it's simple, A = \{0, 1\}A={0,1}A = \{0, 1\}A={0,1}. Finally, the computer only understands sequences of 0000 and 1111 .

Binary, Octal, Decimal and Hexadecimal

Binary

In this section, we will learn how to convert from one basis to another using mathematics. Before that, it's important to understand what we're talking about, what a base actually means, and what we're referring to when we talk about binary, octal, decimal, or hexadecimal bases.

As seen so far, the binary base can be simply represented by the language consisting of words formed by a sequence of 0000 and 1111.

Remark : Here, I am using the term "language" to refer to a set of words to define a base, but a word can just as easily represent a number.

We can give an example of a binary number : 10 = 101010=101010 = 101010=1010. So, how do we read 10101010 in binary? We can represent the number as a 1 \times N1×N1 \times N1×N  table (one row and NNNN columns), where NNNN  corresponds to the number of digits that make it up. This makes :

1111 0000 1111 0000

And now how to get to 10, you have to multiply by the respective power of 2 (relative to the position of the number in the "table"). This makes :

1 \times 2^{3}1×231 \times 2^{3}1×23
0 \times 2^{2}0×220 \times 2^{2}0×22 1 \times 21×21 \times 21×2 0 \times 2^{0}0×200 \times 2^{0}0×20

then add up all the columns. Which does 2^{3} + 2 = 8 + 2 = 1023+2=8+2=102^{3} + 2 = 8 + 2 = 1023+2=8+2=10.

Thus, the set of natural numbers can be written in the form : n =\displaystyle\sum_{i=0}^{+\infty} n_{i}\times 2^{i}n=∑i=0+∞ni×2in =\displaystyle\sum_{i=0}^{+\infty} n_{i}\times 2^{i}n=i=0∑+∞​ni​×2i. Here, the set of (n_i)_{i\in \mathbb{N}}(ni)i∈N(n_i)_{i\in \mathbb{N}}(ni​)i∈N​  contains a certain number of 0000 and 1111 ,then only 0000 .

Remark : What we notice about binary numbers is that all binary numbers begin with a 1111.

Remark : Another point to note is that even numbers end in a 0000, while odd numbers end in a 1111.

Octal

We will quickly move on to the octal base because the construction of octal base numbers is done in the same way as the construction of binary base numbers, differing only by one alphabet.

Since it's done in the same way, we'll simply look at a few examples and then give the general formula directly.

(76543210)_8(76543210)8(76543210)_8(76543210)8​ is an octal number

Here, the set of (n_i)_{i\in \mathbb{N}}(ni)i∈N(n_i)_{i\in \mathbb{N}}(ni​)i∈N​  contains a certain number of 0000, 1111, 2222, 3333, 4444, 5555, 6666 and 7777,then only 0000 .

All integers nnnn can be written in the form n =\displaystyle\sum_{i=0}^{+\infty} n_{i}\times 10^{i}n=∑i=0+∞ni×10in =\displaystyle\sum_{i=0}^{+\infty} n_{i}\times 10^{i}n=i=0∑+∞​ni​×10i. Hexadecimal

Hexadecimal is somewhat unique, not because of how numbers are constructed in this base (which is done in the same way as other bases), but because of the definition of its alphabet. Indeed, until now we have been dealing with bases that were "inferior" to the decimal base; what I mean by this is that the alphabet of the previous bases was a sub-alphabet (subset) of the decimal alphabet.

What makes up the alphabet for base 16161616 ? Well, it's a mixture of numbers and letters. Then, for the number 9, by convention, it was decided that the letter 'AAAA' would replace 10101010 , and the letter 'BBBB' for the number 11111111, and so on... Thus, the largest number in base 16 is 'FFFF' and represents 15151515  in base 10101010.

Hexadecimal 0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8
Decimal 9 10 11 12 13 14 15
Hexadecimal 9 A B C D E F

 

The formula is always the same and we'll generalize it right after this. All integers nnnn can be written in the form n =\displaystyle\sum_{i=0}^{+\infty} n_{i}\times 16^{i}n=∑i=0+∞ni×16in =\displaystyle\sum_{i=0}^{+\infty} n_{i}\times 16^{i}n=i=0∑+∞​ni​×16i. Here, the set of (n_i)_{i\in \mathbb{N}}(ni)i∈N(n_i)_{i\in \mathbb{N}}(ni​)i∈N​  contains a certain number of 0000, 1111, 2222, 3333, 4444, 5555, 6666, 7777, 8888, 9999, AAAA , BBBB, CCCC, DDDD, EEEE and FFFF  then only 0000 .

Now that we've seen all the different bases, it would also be useful to know how to convert from one base to another.

To convert from one base to another, you must always go through the decimal base; in fact, converting from one base to another means applying the formula given for each base each time. Let's try to put this into practice with a small example.

For example, we want to write 1010101010101010 in base 10101010 and convert it to base 8888 (octal).

(1010)_2 = 1 \times(1010)2=1×(1010)_2 = 1 \times(1010)2​=1× 2^2  + 1  \times  2^2  + 1  \times  2^1 + 0 \times 2^022 +1 × 22 +1 × 21+0×202^2  + 1  \times  2^2  + 1  \times  2^1 + 0 \times 2^022 +1 × 22 +1 × 21+0×20 = 10=10= 10=10

and 10 = 1 \times 8^{1} + 2 \times 8^{0}10=1×81+2×8010 = 1 \times 8^{1} + 2 \times 8^{0}10=1×81+2×80 = (12)_{8}=(12)8= (12)_{8}=(12)8​

We've seen the general method, but there are other methods for quickly converting from base 2222 to base 16161616 and vice versa. The same applies to base 2222 and base 8888.

To convert a binary number to a hexadecimal number, simply divide the binary number into blocks of size 4444  starting from the right, then associate each block of 4444 with the corresponding hexadecimal value to obtain the hexadecimal number. For exemple :

(110011001000111010)_2 = 11~~0011~~0010~~0011~~1010(110011001000111010)2=11  0011  0010  0011  1010(110011001000111010)_2 = 11~~0011~~0010~~0011~~1010(110011001000111010)2​=11  0011  0010  0011  1010

However, according to the table, 11 = 411=411 = 411=4, 0011 = 11 = 40011=11=40011 = 11 = 40011=11=4, 0010 = 10 = 30010=10=30010 = 10 = 30010=10=3, 0011 = 11 = 40011=11=40011 = 11 = 40011=11=4, 1010 = A1010=A1010 = A1010=A which gives us

(4434A)_{16}(4434A)16(4434A)_{16}(4434A)16​

The conversion from binary to octal is done using groups of 3333.

 

So you're wondering, if the computer only understands sequences of 0000 and 1111, how does it understand our \texttt{C}C\texttt{C}C program?

Well, here again, the answer is simple: the computer needs a translator, and yes, it's the same question you might ask yourself about how we could understand another language such as Chinese?

So the question to ask is: what could serve as a translator for the computer?

It's a tool called a compiler. A compiler is literally a program that translates the program's language into machine language (binary language). In fact, what we hadn't mentioned before is that there are two types of programming languages : compiled programming languages ​​(here we say that the programs are code) like \texttt{C}C\texttt{C}C, \texttt{C++}C++\texttt{C++}C++, \texttt{Ocaml}Ocaml\texttt{Ocaml}Ocaml and interpreted programming languages ​​(here we say that the programs are scripts) like \texttt{python}python\texttt{python}python, \texttt{bash}bash\texttt{bash}bash.

Now that we know we need a compiler, how can we find one, and how do we install it? For C, there are different compilers, some free, some paid, but the one we're interested in is GCC's. We're going to do a short tutorial on how to install the compiler. The tutorial will depend on the operating system used in the computer.

Tutorial for Linux

sudo apt update
sudo apt update
sudo apt install gcc
sudo apt install gcc
gcc --version
gcc --version

Tutorial for Windows

It is actually possible to have a Linux environment under Windows. You can install a Linux distribution in WSL. WSL is a virtual machine available on Windows .Alternatively, another way to install gcc on Windows is to install MinGW from the following website: https://winlibs.com/ and to take the latest version.

The extraction must be done after the installation. Once the extraction is complete, we verify that the gcc.exe program is indeed located in mingw64/bin. You can place the folder in the program directory or in the root directory of your computer's internal hard drive. Despite all the manipulations we've performed, the computer is still unable to recognize our compiler; in fact, if you type `gcc -v` in a terminal command prompt, an error will occur. Therefore, you need to go into the environment variables.

then go to the path variable

add the path to mingw64\bin

then OK>OK>OK till it close.

Now that you have set up the path, it is possible for the computer to recognize the compiler. If you run the command `gcc -v` in a new command terminal, the compiler should no longer insult you!
